Introduction¶

In this project I will use a dataset that contains information about 10,000 movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDb),which is considered one of the huge datasets for movies on the internet. this data include data such as the cast,the title, the production company and other information to describe each movie. it also contain the user ratings, revenue, and the budget for each movie. Through this analysis , I will try to answer some interesting questions such as :

1. What are the top 20 Movies based on the produciton Budget?

2. What are the top 20 Movies based on the Revenues ?

3. what are the top 20 movies based on the profit ?

4. What are the top 20 Movies based on the User Ratings ?

5. What are the top 20 movies based on the popularity ?

6. What are the top 20 produciton companies ?

7. Which genres are most popular over years?

8. How much was the production of movies over years?

Finally , I will provide some visualizations to describe the answers

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Tip: Now that you've trimmed and cleaned your data, you're ready to move on to exploration. Compute statistics and create visualizations with the goal of addressing the research questions that you posed in the Introduction section. It is recommended that you be systematic with your approach. Look at one variable at a time, and then follow it up by looking at relationships between variables.

Research Question 1 (what are the top 20 movies based on the production budget? )¶

In [163]:
# Udacity: Use this, and more code cells, to explore your data. Don't forget to add
#   Markdown cells to document your observations and findings.

#this will be based on their production budget
#calculate the top 20 movies based on their  budget
movies_with_budgets = tmdb[['original_title','budget']]

#sort the column of budget_adj in Descnding order
movies_with_budgets = movies_with_budgets.sort_values(by = 'budget',ascending = False).head(20)

#plot the data
movies_with_budgets.plot(x = 'original_title', y = 'budget', kind = 'bar',color='blue',figsize = (13,9),fontsize=15);
plt.title(' \nthe top 20 movies based on the budget\n',fontsize = 25)
plt.xlabel("movies", fontsize=15)
plt.ylabel("budget,US Dollar", fontsize=15)
plt.grid(True)
plt.savefig('top 20 movies on budget.jpg')
plt.show();

According the shown Figure , The Top of the Top 20 movies in the production budget is The Warrior's Way with budget of 425,000,000.0 US Dollar , that movie was produced by Boram Entertainment inc. and directed by Sngmoo Lee.

While the last movie in those top 20 of the highest budget includes three movies The Chronicles of Narnia : Prince Caspian released 2008, Men in Black 3 released in 2012 and Man of Steel released in 2013 with budget of 225,000,000 US Dollar for each of them.

# I got this function from another Data analysis project about TMDB Dataset

#call the function for counting the movies of each genre.
def count(x):
#concatenate all the rows of the genrs.
    tmdb_plot = tmdb[x].str.cat(sep = '|')
    tmdb_split = pd.Series(tmdb_plot.split('|'))
#conts each of the genre and return.
    count = tmdb_split.value_counts(ascending=False)
    return count

production_companies = count('production_companies').head(20)

#check for the top 20 companies
production_companies_top=production_companies

#will describe years into groups ( 10 years for each group)
bin_edges =[1959,1970,1980,1990,2000,2010,2015]

#label for each group 
bin_names = ['1960/1970','1970/1980','1980/1990','1990/2000','2000/2010','2010/2015']

#create years level column
tmdb['year_level'] = pd.cut(tmdb['release_year'], bin_edges, labels=bin_names)
tmdb.tail()

#call the function for counting the total of movies for each year.
title_count=tmdb.groupby('year_level')['original_title'].count()

#plot data
years=tmdb.groupby("year_level").size()
title_count = title_count.plot(kind = 'pie',figsize=(18,10),fontsize =15,autopct=lambda p: '{:.2f}%({:.0f})'.format(p,(p/100)*years.sum()))

title_count = title_count.plot(kind = 'pie',figsize=(22,17),fontsize =15)

First I have to say that , TMDB dataset is very very rich in information. you can get alot of analysis out of that data,however, their are some wrangling for the data must be done before any analysis , this is beacuse the dataset contains null and zero values in some features. also there was one record wsa duplicated . i norder to have good analysis all these zero and null values have to be removed.for example if we make correlation for any data contains zero values this will misslead. Therfore it is important to do data cleaning before the dataset's investigation.
